In [[parliamentary procedure]], especially the [[Westminster system]], a document is '''laid before the house''' or '''Laid on the Table of the House''' when it is formally recognised as having been made available for members of a [[deliberative assembly]] to read.<ref name="uk-parl-glossary">{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/site-information/glossary/laid-or-laying-before-parliament/|title=Laid or laying (before Parliament)|work=Glossary|publisher=UK Parliament|accessdate=11 July 2014}}</ref> Documents produced by official bodies or in response to orders from parliament are required to be laid before the house.<ref name="uk-parl-glossary" /> These documents inform members in their deliberations.
Originally, a physical copy of the document was placed on the table in the assembly chamber.<ref name="uk-parl-glossary" /> This is no longer the case, with statutes and [[rules of order]] determining the mode by which a document is recognised as having been laid.<ref name="tso-guidelines" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1966/en/act/pub/0010/print.html|title=Houses of the Oireachtas (Laying of Documents) Act, 1966|work=[[Irish Statute Book]]|accessdate=11 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/Geo6/11-12/59|title=Laying of Documents Before Parliament (Interpretation) Act 1948|work=[[UK Statute Law Database]]|accessdate=11 July 2014}}</ref> Some such documents are published, as for example the [[command paper]]s issued by the UK Parliament.<ref name="tso-guidelines">{{cite web|url=http://www.tso.co.uk/documents/presentationToParliament-Publishing.pdf|title=Guidance and requirements for laying papers before the House of Commons and their publication|date=April 2009|publisher=Journal Office|accessdate=11 July 2014}}</ref> Others may not be published.<ref name="tso-guidelines" /> [[Electronic publishing]] is common for documents laid in recent decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oireachtas.ie/viewdoc.asp?DocID=9529|title=Laying of Documents before the Houses of the Oireachtas - Frequently Asked Questions|publisher=Oireachtas|accessdate=11 July 2014}}</ref> [[Parliamentary privilege]] may extend to documents published.<ref name="tso-guidelines"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/parliamentarybusiness/26506.aspx|title=Chapter 14: Laying and Publication of Documents|work=Parliamentary Business|publisher=Scottish Parliament|accessdate=11 July 2014}}</ref> The Irish [[Department of Finance (Ireland)|Department of Finance]] guidelines state, "It should be especially noted that documents to be laid before the Houses of [[Oireachtas]] must not be published before being so laid. A breach of this direction is a serious infringement of parliamentary privilege."<ref>Department of the Taoiseach 2006, §4</ref>
